<br>
  Tank<br>
  Medic<br>
  Crowd controller<br>
  + others<br>
<br>
<br>
Most people interpret that to be war/cleric/ench+others since the warrior, cleric, and enchanter are the &quot;purest&quot; form of the roles mentioned.  Even people thinking they are putting together non-classic groups are filling these roles.<br>
<br>
When I put together groups (which is why I don't complain about not being able to find them) I look for the following roles in the following order (once you get the first two the group builds itself <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
  Cleric (at 58th nothing else will work)<br>
  Crowd controller<br>
  Tank<br>
  Backup healer / Buffer<br>
  Extra-damage / Utility<br>
<br>
What a lot of people seem to overlook is that depending on the encounter and the skill of your group there is a LOT of leeway in filling the roles.<br>
<br>
  -Kasia &lt;Spirit Bond&gt; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wezloc>WEZLOC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 411<br> <font color=#333333>(3/28/02 1:15:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What is the definition of  the &quot;Classic Group?&quot</span><hr size=1> I would agree with that.<br>
<br>
Enchanter, Cleric, Warrior are really the foundation of a classic group.<br>
<br>
However with the improvement of the knight classes warriors can be easily replaced and Sk, and Pallies bring there own set of skills to the table that help a ton.  <br>
<br>
Bard, Shaman, Paladin is also a good start to a group. Not as defined as the top 3 classes but basically offers the same roles when grouping.<br>
<br>
But when I am forming groups with my bard I look for a Tank, cleric, shaman. Shamans are really overlooked sometimes but Shaman, Druid, Bard, Paladin, Rogue, Monk is a killer group. Paladins can rez 90% at 60 and with stuns and slow the damage being taken by the group is so low that a druid can be the primary healer with ease. Also since rogues dont take damage normally and monks have mend this type group will outdo a classic group.  But at the end of the day when we talk about what damage classes you want in a group...Mage is 4th on my list behind Rogue, Monk, and then Ranger.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uzacatac.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Zacatac</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 688<br> <font color=#333333>(3/28/02 1:16:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=176.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What is the definition of  the &quot;Classic Group?&quot</span><hr size=1> Think I agree with zephyr the most.<br>
<br>
